<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Look for Oak Integration, Not Oak Dominance</strong> - The best Chardonnays show seamless oak integration where vanilla and spice enhance rather than mask the fruit. Premium producers like Chablis Grand Cru or Burgundy whites use older barrels (2-4 years) and longer lees aging, creating creamy textures without overwhelming butter or vanilla notes. Avoid Chardonnays where oak flavors jump out immediately—they often use new oak chips or younger barrels that haven't mellowed.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at 50-55°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Unlike lighter whites, the best Chardonnays need slightly warmer serving temperatures to reveal their complexity. Premium oak-aged Chardonnays served too cold (below 45°F) will hide their nuanced mineral notes and textural richness. Remove from refrigeration 15-20 minutes before serving, or use a wine thermometer to hit that sweet spot where both fruit and tertiary flavors shine.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanter, but Consider Breathing Time</strong> - Top Chardonnays rarely need decanting, but aged examples (8+ years) benefit from 30-45 minutes of breathing in the glass. Young, high-quality Chardonnays from producers like Kistler or Roulot can be tight upon opening—pour a small taste, then let the bottle breathe briefly to allow the wine's full aromatic profile to emerge.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy-Style Bowls for Maximum Aroma</strong> - The best Chardonnays deserve proper glassware with a wider bowl than standard white wine glasses. The larger surface area concentrates the wine's complex aromatics—from citrus zest and stone fruit to hazelnut and brioche notes developed during lees aging. Avoid narrow flutes that compress these layered aromas.</li>

