<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between oaked and unoaked Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Oaked Chardonnay undergoes barrel fermentation or aging, developing flavors of vanilla, butter, and toast alongside tropical fruit notes. Unoaked versions showcase pure fruit character with crisp acidity, green apple, and citrus flavors without any wood influence. The choice between them depends on your preference for richer, creamier textures versus bright, mineral-driven styles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I identify a high-quality Chardonnay without breaking the bank?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Chardonnays from emerging regions like Sonoma Coast, Willamette Valley, or Chablis premier cru vineyards, which often offer exceptional quality-to-price ratios. Seek producers who practice sustainable farming and use native yeast fermentation, as these techniques typically indicate more thoughtful winemaking. Avoid mass-produced bottles with heavy manipulation like excessive oak chips or added sugar.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve different styles of Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve crisp, unoaked Chardonnays like Chablis at 45-50°F to preserve their mineral clarity and acidity. Rich, oaked Chardonnays from Burgundy or California benefit from slightly warmer serving temperatures of 50-55°F, which allows their complex flavors and creamy textures to fully express themselves. Over-chilling masks the wine's complexity, while serving too warm emphasizes alcohol and diminishes freshness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is expensive Chardonnay always better than affordable options?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Not necessarily—many exceptional Chardonnays exist in the $15-30 range, particularly from regions like Languedoc, Oregon, or small Burgundy appellations. Expensive bottles often reflect prestigious vineyard sites, limited production, or established reputations rather than inherently superior quality. Focus on producers known for their winemaking philosophy and terroir expression rather than price alone.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when choosing Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is assuming all Chardonnays taste the same—the grape expresses dramatically different characteristics depending on climate, soil, and winemaking techniques. Many people also avoid Chardonnay entirely due to past experiences with overly oaked, butter-bomb styles from the 1990s, missing out on today's more balanced, terroir-driven expressions. Another mistake is not considering food pairings, as different Chardonnay styles complement vastly different cuisines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age the best Chardonnays?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top-tier Chardonnays from Burgundy's grand cru vineyards can age gracefully for 10-20 years, developing honeyed complexity and deeper mineral notes. Premium California Chardonnays typically peak within 5-8 years, though exceptional vintages may last longer. Unoaked styles are generally best consumed within 2-3 years to preserve their fresh fruit character and vibrant acidity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are good alternatives if I want something similar to premium Chardonnay?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For those seeking Chardonnay's richness and complexity, try white Rhône blends featuring Roussanne and Marsanne, or aged Chenin Blanc from the Loire Valley. If you prefer the mineral, crisp style of unoaked Chardonnay, explore Sancerre (Sauvignon Blanc), Grüner Veltliner from Austria, or Albariño from Spain. These alternatives often provide similar food-pairing versatility at different price points.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Chardonnay a good choice for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Chardonnay is an excellent gateway wine because it offers a wide spectrum of styles to explore, from crisp and food-friendly to rich and complex. Beginners should start with moderately oaked versions from regions like Sonoma County or Pouilly-Fuissé, which balance fruit, oak, and acidity without overwhelming the palate. The grape's versatility with food also makes it practical for learning wine and food pairing principles.</p>
